column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: The anti-austerity leftist party, Podemos, and the reform minded centrist party, Cuidadanos, are hoping to capitalize on the steady erosion of support for Spain's primary political parties, Partido Popular (PP) and Partido Socialista Obrero EspaÃ±ol (PSOE) (Bloomberg, EconoTimes, CNBC). Elections are expected to be held on or before 20 December 2015. Updated on 2/22/16: The question on Spain's election has been reopened for forecasting as the parties are still working to put together a governing coalition. The end date will continue to be extended until a new governing coalition is formed or new elections are scheduled. Updated on 4/8/16: The question has been reopened. Negotiations on a power-sharing agreement are ongoing, and a new deadline of May 2nd has been set (Agence France-Presse via Yahoo!). The question will be suspended at 11:59pm Pacific on May 3rd in the absence of a new governing coalition, the scheduling of elections, or an extension of the negotiation deadline.

The developments this week have been interesting (El Pais and other major Spanish papers have the details).

The developments this week have been interesting (El Pais and other major Spanish papers have the details). Citizens has agreed an acceptable platform with the Socialists. This reduces the chances that Podemos is part of a formal coalition (I have already had them at 0% for some time) and is really a gambit to get the PP to abstain during the vote on government formation on March 5th. It puts the PP in a difficult position. They had declined the chance to form a government first as they felt it would fail and damage credibility and so wanted the Socialists to try first (and fail). All along the PP has favoured a unity minority government where the PSOE and C would informally support the PP on a limited set of reforms and new elections late in 2016. Instead it is now the Socialists who are trying to do exactly this with Sanchez as the leader. The PP need not vote for Sanchez- merely abstaining will get him in the door. However, I don't see the PP abstaining and I believe this effort will fail. That leaves four scenarios 1) no government, new elections in Spring 2) Rather than the PSOE trying to head a government, it is Ciudadanos that is given the final chance and they are able to form a temporary minority government with votes of PSOE and PP 3) the PP asks for a turn to form a government, but they depose Rajoy and appoint a new leader in return for an abstention by the PSOE or 4) The Socialists try to move left and re-attract Podemos into the mix (note it will be difficult to get the support of both Podemos and Ciudadanos).

Today's contestants seem to be PSOE and Ciudadanos, who are now groveling around to muster enough votes from somewhere--anywhere, really--to get their arrangement approved. The latest poll putting Podemos ahead of the PSOE changes everything. It probably nudges Podemos in the direction of wanting new elections. But it also increases the pressure on PSOE to form a government. It increases the pressure on the non-secessionists to get into a coalition. And it makes the PSOE-Podemos disagreement about regional autonomy even more intractable.
No change.

The Socialistas are probably willing to give up pretty much the whole store to avoid new elections, which recent polls show would result in their coming third behind Podemos. Unluckily for PSOE, the only ones they can surrender to plausibly are Podemos, who since they will likely do better in new elections have little reason to chat with Sanchez. None of this is likely to get sorted in the next couple of weeks, one suspects.

Well, let's see--the King has asked PSOE to put together a gummint. PSOE + Podemos is not enough, and Podemos won't play with Ciudadanos, they say. The regional factions are unlikely to join a formal coalition with PSOE, and vice versa, what with one thing and another. PSOE says they need at least a month to get sorted.

We're into the end-game now that the Socialists have been invited to form a coalition. Ciudadanos is too small to be the only partner. Podemos alone only works if the Socialists include regional parties wanting regional autonomy - that is unlikely. There are therefore only two possible outcomes: failure, or a coalition that includes both P and C. I think the attractions of being in power will prove great enough to lead to some kind of agreement.

The only coalition geometry acceptable by both voters and party structures includes, most probably, PSOE, PODEMOS, IU and regional parties, It is clear that i) a big centrist pact is neither popular nor viable; ii) PODEMOS and Ciudadanos are mutually exclusive; iii) the same with PP/Ciudadanos and every autonomist party. In conclusion, either we have PODEMOS in the ruling coalition or no ruling coalition at all, which would mean new elections.

My prediction went stale. I expected that minor parties will undergo the fizz that happened to MoDem or ToPotamos, but polls show the opposite. The Portuguese elections are somewhat suggestive to what we should expect. Even d'Hondt method of distribution is the same, muddying the numbers from the polls. The only difference is in Spain the four forces are at an arm's length. In Portugal, right-wing parties acknowledged their alliance before the elections, while the left-wing parties took an extremely long time to agree. Should the Portuguese socialists be more effective at alliance-forging, we would have had the equivalent of a POD + PSOE from start; instead, we saw the equivalent of PP + C's for a few days. In Spain the polls indicate even better scores for the second-tier parties (compare https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:ElectionMonthlyAverageGraphPortugal2015.png to https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:OpinionPollingSpainGeneralElection2015.png ) suggesting that it will be even more unlikely for either of the two main parties to govern alone. So I am giving the NONE option a very small chance. One one hand, the left binomial sums a bit higher than the right. On the other, the d'Hondt method favors the largest party, thus helping the PP+C's, where the smaller partner is less important. I am going out on a limb by thinking that d'Hondt-based redistribution will squash the 2-4% advantage the PSOE+POD have. In summary, I am revising up both "one party" options, and down "none".

How likely is a coalition at all? A significant fact is that there has never been a coalition government in Spanish politics since the transition to democracy in the late 70s. When insufficient votes exist, parties have prefered to run minority governments. However, this election is unprecedentedly tight, with opinion polls putting the big parties with only 55% of the vote between them, as opposed to ~80% of the vote in the past.
Reform is in the air.

The 2 main political parties (PP and PSOE) are still the 2 leading parties. A coalition between them (and maybe some regional parties) should have a majority. These 2 parties are natural opponents, but a coalition of national unity is a possibility. Since one of the main parties will still be necessary, that means that a coalition with both POD and CUID is unlikely, since one of them (and some regional parties) would probably secure a majority. It is still a possibility in case the main party wants play CUID and POD against one another. If only one party becomes a part of the government, CUID would have a better chance, since it's policies are closer to the centre.

Spain's economy is growing and the country appears to have avoided the fate of Greece. They're still in the Eurozone. While both Podemos and Ciudadanos have potential as 'young Turks', that still may not translate to a seat (or seats) at the [governing] table. Realistically, I see the PSOE (Socialist Workers Party) gaining more seats rather than Podemos getting any. Podemos's values seem to align strongly with Greece's Syriza Party and their performance so far in the handling of Greece's crisis has been pretty dismal. Of the two parties, Ciudadanos, with their 'reform-minded, centrist' platform may have a better chance in winning anything. I believe the Spanish people will opt for status quo.
